Listening to the two factions – the pro-BBI and the seemingly anti-BBI – one can never be certain of who their genuineness.
There are all signs of dishonesty and selfishness from both camps. A keen eye will notice that the duel has narrowed down to a contest between two individuals.
Mr. Raila Odinga, for instance, seems to have sworn to teach the Deputy President a lesson so that any proposition from the latter is responded to by a defiant ‘nobody can stop reggae’ slogan.
Elsewhere, the visibly agitated DP has fallen into the trap of his nemesis, fighting to disprove him in a manner suggestive of a higher ‘calling’.
With these two, consensus may never be in sight. In fact, the fuss around BBI can easily be attributed to acrimony between the two, a phenomenon that will definitely rope in their followers come the 2022 elections. Residents of Mombasa have been eagerly waiting the commissioning of the bridge. Ms Nthenya was freed without any charges being preferred against her. Just last week, Justice James Rika recused himself from the case after tempers flared in court.